y writing from other places. The Edinburgh Companion to Contemporary Scottish Poetry is the definitive guide to this flourishing poetic scene. Its chapters examine Scottish poetry in all three of the nation's languages. It analyses many thematic preoccupations: tradition and innovation; revolutions in gender; the importance of place; the aesthetic politics of devolution. These chapters are complemented by extended close readings of the work of key poets that have defined this era, including Edwin Morgan, Kathleen Jamie, Don Paterson, Aonghas MacNeacail and John Burnside. Key FeaturesA thorough guide to contemporary Scottish poetry and poets, making the book an ideal course textReflects the ways in which the work of Scottish poets reflects a radical cultural independence following DevolutionProvides authoritative essays by the leading experts in the fieldIncludes a valuable synoptic bibliography  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDialect poetry, ScottishxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish poetryxScottish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aScottish Gaelic poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aScottish Gaelic poetryy21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aScottish poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aScottish poetryy21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aCraig, Cairns, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFazzini, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillis, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHubbard, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackay, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, Kirsten, econtributor.4ct